<section>
  <div>
    <h1>CSS variables</h1>
    <p>CSS variables are variables we create using properties, so we can later re-use them.</p>
    <p>For example if you used variables adding color, it would be very easy to swap color theme in one go.</p>
    <p>We create it by adding it to the :root, and define our variable like this --my-color-var.</p>
    <p>After that we add what we want it to do, in this case we want it to use a color, --my-color-var:blue;</p>
    <p>By using our variables when creating classes etc instead of the properties, if we later decide that we would like to<br>
      change something, instead of changeing the property value of each class, we could simple change it in our variable and it would be<br>
      applied to all our classes.
    </p>
    <p>CSS variables are not compatible with the IE web browser.</p>
  </div>
  <div>
    <h3>Code example</h3>
    <pre>
      <code>
        /* Variables */
        :root {
          --bg-color-primary:coral;
          --color-primary:white;
          --bg-color-secondary:white;
          --color-secondary:black;
          --margin-1em:1em;
          --primary-border:1px orange solid;
        }
        /* Asign to class */

        .class{
          color: var(--color-primary);
        }
        body{
          background-color: var(--bg-color-primary);
        }
        #id{
          margin: var(--margin-1em);
        }
      </code>
    </pre>
  </div>
</section>
